elements.text: `master-blaster`  github.com/Twitchkidd/master-blaster
PyPi
master-blaster
package
Install!

The important bits here are in setup.py and
Pipfile!
setup.py:
  ...
  install_requires=["questionary", "requests"],
  scripts=["bin/master-blaster"],
  ...

Pipfile:
  ...
  [packages]
  master-blaster = {path = "."}
  ...

This makes sure the program
can use the questionary and
requests libraries!

And these two together
make `master-blaster`
a runnable command.

/bin/master-blaster

1 - Introduce the program
2 - Run user authentication
3 - Get the program options
4 - Make the changes
5 - Best wishes, wave goodbye

Bonus:
* - Flag testing environment
* - Get and set branch again
      while testing
* - Catch-all exception handling

.../lib/actions

Folder for modules to
live in! (Most of the code!)

Folder for modules that
run shell commands and

.../lib/reporting.py

Anything involving large
amounts of text and
the user interface

Main parts:
* - Introductory text
* - User interface for auth
* - User interface for the
      options wizard
* - check_names(repos):
      handles sorting repos based
      on presence of branches of
      the target name and/or master
      and whether there's a local
      copy of the repo (optionally)
* - Reporting back after the program
      runs, listing changes and any
      errors
* - Waving bye-bye

../lib/auth.py

1 - Get the username
2 - Get the personal
      access token
3 - Get the initial list
      of repos

Bonus, handle:
* - No Internet connection 
* - Bad requests
* - No repos to work on

there's an
__init__.py in

.../actions/network.py

Anything related to
network requests!

1 - Attempt to get the
     initial list of repos
2 - Check remote repos
      for presence of
      master and target
      name branches
3 - Update the GitHub
       default branch

.../lib/options.py

1 - Get the user preferences for naming mode,
     target name or names, to use local directories,
     what root directory to use, whether to remove
     cloned repos, and whether to add the git alias
2 - Get local repos (optionally)
3 - Check the branches of local (optionally) and
      remote repos to classify what actions can
      be taken

Note:
  `check_branches()` is populating the data with flags
    for whether a repo has the target or master (or
    a 'third' as primary) locally and remotely
  `check_names()` is the function that sorts the repos
    into categories based on the presence of those branches

.../actions/shell.py

This file holds all functions that run shell processes and
deal with the file system!

The functions handling files are get_local_token() for cached personal
  access tokens, get_local_repos(), get_local_repo_url() for getting
  the URL for the remote for local repos, and get_current_branch().

The functions running shell processes all use a function defined as
  process_runner(string, process, *args) that runs the process, handles
  logging any processes that are run and any errors, and handles strings
  in stderr that may mean it's not really an error.

The shell processes run by master blaster:

* - set git branch
* - list git branches
* - rename git branch
* - push to remote and
      set upstream
* - delete remote branch

* - make directory
* - clone a repo
* - delete local branch
* - checkout a branch
* - fetch remote refs
* - unset the upstream

* - set local's upstream
* - update symbolic refs
* - remove directories
* - and add a git alias
     `git new` that will
     initialize a repo
     with the target name,
     if there's just one

There's also check_local_branches() that runs
  git branch on local repos to check for master
  and target name.

.../lib/dispatch.py

1 - First are defined the procedures for each
     state of a repo that can be acted upon
2 - `run()` calls these on repos ready for it,
       as well as adding the git alias, and
       handles errors and cleanup
3 - Then it calls for a report to be run on
       what happened, and displayed

Bonus:
  Control over flow in error handling allows
    for any changes to (optimistically) be
    set back, if there *are* errors
